                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 819.00/356.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Extracts.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Panama</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-01-27">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 27, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Minister of Panama at Washington has been instructed to consult the
                    Department of State as to whether the American Government would be willing to
                    supervise the elections. Mendoza tells me that such supervision would appear to
                    be the only way to secure absolute impartiality.</p>
                <p>The intention of President Arosemena to take leave on February 2 was officially
                    communicated to-day to the Supreme Court.</p>
                <p>Boyd, the Second Designate, is opposed to Arosemena’s candidacy. The latter has
                    instructed the Minister of Panama to consult the Department as to his
                    constitutional eligibility.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodge.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
